english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent to Lord Yongcheon Upon His Journey to Songgyeong
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the year Gyemi, Lord Yongcheon resolved to journey to Songgyeong and requested that I compose words for his departure. I replied to him thus:

    "To study the deeds of the ancients through the pages of books and befriend them from afar is not equal to seeking out the places where they dwelt and imagining the spirit they left behind. To hear of the splendor of mountains and rivers through hearsay and distant musing is not equal to climbing those heights oneself and witnessing their full majesty with one's own eyes. This is why the Grand Historian journeyed through the Yangtze and Huai rivers, ascended Mount Kuaiji, studied in the ancient capitals of Qi and Lu, passed through Liang and Chu before returning home. This too is why Tao Yuanming wished to seek out the traces of the sages in the central plains.

    Songgyeong is the ancient capital of five hundred years past. It possesses the grandeur of mountains and rivers embracing it within and without, and bears the marks of both ancient and modern figures. Thus many lovers of antiquity journey there to wander. I myself, with my home in the western regions, have passed through Songgyeong and once paid reverence to the royal residence where our founding ancestor dwelt before ascending the throne. The mountains and rivers embrace and protect it; the auspicious qi hangs thick and verdant; the temples stand as they did yesterday; the imperial presence feels near enough to touch. I gazed upon them, prostrated myself, lingered reluctant to depart.

    I proceeded to seek out the ruins of the old Koryo dynasty. What met my eyes were only crumbling walls, scattered foundation stones, and thorny brambles. The grandeur of a thousand gates and ten thousand households could not be seen. Though the cycles of rise and fall, of going and coming, succeed one another as the heavens decree, I could not help but feel the poignancy that strikes the heart of later generations.

    Moreover, the palaces of nobles and officials, the gardens and stones that once vied with one another in beauty—after centuries of the mountains shifting and valleys changing—few remain. Often beneath grass and weeds, the old foundations still stand. When I inquire of the elders, they sigh and say: 'Ah, this was the home of such a one; that was the home of another.' Yet examining the deeds these men accomplished, some stir admiration and respect; some call forth lament and condolence; some are scarcely worthy of mention; and some provoke such anger that one's hair bristles, fists clench, and curses fly unbidden.

    Alas! In their days of glory, when their power blazed like fire, each believed himself lord over his age. How could they have known that after death—whether their names flow down in fragrant remembrance or foul infamy—neither can be hidden from the world? From this I have gained deeper understanding: that wealth and rank are not worthy of trust.

    As for the splendor of mountains and rivers, I have always traveled in haste, lacking the leisure to don my hiking shoes and truly explore. Yet riding with the flow, I beheld celestial peaks and sacred mountains, clouds ascending and waves surging across hundreds of li until they tower over Songgyeong. All the summits compete in beauty; all the valleys rush with waters; green embraces and folds upon folds appear like a painted scroll. I seemed to glimpse immortals subsisting on mist and sacred fungus, riding phoenixes beyond the world's bounds, smiling at my petty confinement.

    And the secret splendor of Cape Maa, the fantastic majesty of Nine-Dragon Pools—these visit my heart often, yet I have never found the fortune to go there and fulfill my longing. Perhaps the maker of all things guards these places jealously, lest dusty mortal footprints sully their pristine emptiness.

    Yet you, my lord, though dwelling in wealth and station, harbor quiet passion for forest and spring. Having cast off the tangles of worldly refinement, you ride forth westward alone. You will explore what I have yearned to see but could not—the renowned territories and wondrous realms where sages dwell, with flowers and trees of jade whose names none know. You will broaden the scope of your remarkable learning. Standing upon the highest peaks, gazing across the vast expanse, all the wrinkled forms of creation will pile before you; all phenomena will reveal themselves. The universe stretches high and deep; wind and cloud transform endlessly. This alone will invigorate your spirit and sweep clear your heart. Your vigor will grow bolder, your thoughts more extraordinary, and when they pour forth as poetry and prose, they will flow ceaselessly as if from an inexhaustible spring, achieving grandeur as though blessed by divine aid. In ascending heights to compose verse, you will surely not yield to the ancients, and the scrolls from your journey shall surely fill many volumes.

    I shall watch with eager eyes for your return. Through the splendor of your words, I shall glimpse something of the majesty of those mountains and rivers. Thus my deep sorrow at not having journeyed there myself may find itself eight or nine parts assuaged."
  footnotes:
    - 'Gyemi: Refers to the year 1583 in the reign of King Seonjo of Joseon.'
    - 'The Grand Historian (太史公): Sima Qian, whose Records of the Grand Historian documents his extensive travels throughout ancient China.'
    - 'Mount Kuaiji (會稽): An important historical site in ancient China, visited by many scholars and officials.'
    - 'Tao Yuanming (陶淵明): A celebrated poet and recluse of the Eastern Jin dynasty, known for his love of nature and philosophical temperament.'
    - 'Songgyeong (松京): Another name for Gaeseong, the capital of the Koryo dynasty for several centuries before Joseon was founded.'
    - 'The founding ancestor: References the founding of Joseon dynasty and the royal residence in Gaeseong.'
    - The poetic conceit of immortals riding phoenixes reflects the Daoist and literary tradition of viewing sages as transcending worldly concerns.
